subsection.p:
      Vector equationequivalence with system of equations
      An equation involving vectors with n coordinates is the same as n equations involving only numbers.  For example, the equation
    x\vec{1 2 6} + y \vec{-1 -2 -1} = \vec{8 16 3}
    simplifies to
    \vec{ x 2x 6x} + \vec{-y -2y -y} = \vec{8 16 3}
\sptxt{or}
\spalignsysdelims()\syseq{ x - y; 2x - 2y; 6x - y} = \vec{8 16 3}.

    For two vectors to be equal, all of their coordinates must be equal, so this is just the system of linear equations
    \spalignsysdelims\{.\syseq{x - y = 8; 2x - 2y = 16; 6x - y = 3\rlap.}

solution.p:
This means: can we solve the equation
      x\vec{1 2 6} + y \vec{-1 -2 -1} = \vec{8 16 3}
      in the unknowns x,y?  This vector equation translates into the system of linear equations
      \syseq{x - y = 8; 2x - 2y = 16; 6x - y = 3\rlap.}
      We form an augmented matrix and row reduce:
      \amat{1 -1 8; 2 -2 16; 6 -1 3}
      \quad\xrightarrow{\text{RREF}}\quad
      \amat{1 0 -1; 0 1 -9; 0 0 0}.

      Thus the equation is consistent, and the solution is x=-1 and y=-9.  We conclude that  \vec{ 8 16 3} is indeed a linear combination of \vec{1 2 6} and \vec{-1 -2 -1}, with coefficients -1 and -9:
      -\vec{1 2 6} -9\vec{-1 -2 -1} = \vec{8 16 3}.

subsection.p:
In order to actually solve the vector equation
    x\textcolor{seq-red}{\vec{1 2 6}}
    + y \textcolor{seq-green}{\vec{-1 -2 -1}}
    = \textcolor{seq-blue}{\vec{8 16 3}},
    one has to solve the system of linear equations
    \spalignsysdelims\{.\syseq{x - y = 8; 2x - 2y = 16; 6x - y = 3\rlap.}
    This means forming the augmented matrix
    \def\r{\color{seq-red}}\def\g{\color{seq-green}}\def\b{\color{seq-blue}}
    \amat{\r1 \g-1 \b8; \r2 \g-2 \b16; \r6 \g-1 \b3}
    and row reducing.  Note that the columns of the augmented matrix are the vectors from the original vector equation, so it is not actually necessary to write the system of equations: one can go directly from the vector equation to the augmented matrix by smooshing the vectors together.

